  "staging": {
    "source": "director",
    "movements": [
      {
        "turn": 1,
        "name": "The Verdict of Style",
        "intent": "Gather the room around the find and let its certainty build — establish the nocturne as object and question before a single proof is laid down."
      },
      {
        "turn": 8,
        "name": "The Dating",
        "intent": "Turn the room from the warm question of who toward the cold question of when — make the leaf's age the live demand, so the first dated fact lands with full weight and the style-verdict is set at risk."
      },
      {
        "turn": 16,
        "name": "The Sounding",
        "intent": "Turn the room from the cold question of WHEN — now answered, the leaf fixed in its season and a person placed within it — toward the question a date can never reach: where the music came from. Make the nocturne stop being a dated object and become a sounding thing whose origin must be traced, so that source becomes the live demand and the next fact about the music itself lands with full weight."
      },
      {
        "turn": 23,
        "name": "The Counter-Tide",
        "intent": "The question of source is open, and into the opening the tide runs backward. Let the empty place in the named house seem to fill at last — and fill with the name the room had set aside, returned now wearing the roof and the song it once lacked. Hold the pull of it: make access feel like proof, so that presence — the season already fixed, the body already placed elsewhere — must be set against it and not merely assumed. The temptation should be strong enough that withstanding it is an act, not a reflex."
      },
      {
        "turn": 27,
        "name": "The Hand",
        "intent": "Source is settled and the counter-tide spent; two names have held the song, but the leaves have been read every way save one — as the work of a hand. Turn the drama from who had the source to whose hand moved on the page, and let presence and source, now both proven for the single name, bear down on the one thing still missing."
      }
    ],
    "tutorNotes": []
  },
